<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="270" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,1564,1728]" box="[160,409,1564,1590]" pageId="5" pageNumber="270">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,1564,1590]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="270">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,1564,1728]" pageId="5" pageNumber="270">Body elongate, narrow, white-beige or brown, with a discontinuous dark brown band over cephalic shield. Cephalic shield longer than shell. Parapodia short, not overlapping. Shell completely covered by mantle. Individuals likely hide in the sediment during the day and are active at night.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="271" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[160,1155,142,237]" box="[160,252,142,168]" pageId="6" pageNumber="271">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,142,168]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="271">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[160,1155,142,237]" pageId="6" pageNumber="271">Specimens were found crawling at night on rocks with algae and sediment between rocky outcrops.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
